-- Enrichment marathon batch: Groundcover, Group Office, GrowthBar, GrowthBook, GrowthLoop, Gumroad, Guru, Gusto

-- ── Groundcover ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Groundcover is an eBPF-powered observability platform giving engineering teams zero-instrumentation metrics, logs, traces, and AI observability across Kubernetes environments.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Freemium, usage-based (per monitored Kubernetes node)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$Free (Pro from $30 per host per month)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2021, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Tel Aviv, Israel$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Groundcover Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Groundcover review covering its eBPF observability engine, Kubernetes monitoring, node-based pricing tiers, key features, pros and cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Groundcover is a full-stack observability platform purpose-built for cloud-native and Kubernetes environments. Instead of asking developers to add SDKs, agents, or manual instrumentation to every service, Groundcover deploys an adaptive eBPF sensor as a DaemonSet on each node in a cluster. That sensor hooks into the Linux kernel to automatically capture metrics, logs, distributed traces, and application-layer protocol data (HTTP, gRPC, Postgres, Redis, Kafka, and more) the moment a workload starts running, with no code changes and no redeploys required. The company positions this zero-instrumentation approach as a direct challenge to legacy Application Performance Monitoring (APM) vendors such as Datadog and New Relic, whose agent-based and ingestion-priced models Groundcover argues create blind spots in lower environments like staging and development, where teams are reluctant to pay to monitor everything. Groundcover was founded in 2021 and is headquartered in Tel Aviv, Israel. The company emerged from the observability and eBPF research community and has grown quickly on the strength of its kernel-level sensor technology, which was highlighted by Forbes and The New Stack as one of the more technically distinctive approaches to next-generation observability. Groundcover has raised a total of roughly 60 million dollars, including a 35 million dollar Series B round announced in April 2025 led by Zeev Ventures, with participation from existing backers including Heavybit, Jibe Ventures, and Angular Ventures. The company has publicly framed this raise as fuel to expand aggressively into the US market and compete more directly with incumbent observability platforms. Architecturally, Groundcover is built around a Bring Your Own Cloud (BYOC) deployment model: the data plane, including the storage backend and the eBPF sensors, runs inside the customer's own cloud account or Kubernetes cluster, so raw telemetry data never leaves the customer's environment. Only a thin control plane and UI layer are hosted by Groundcover, or, on the On-Premise plan, self-hosted as well. This is a meaningfully different security and cost posture than SaaS-only observability vendors that require all logs, metrics, and traces to be shipped to a third-party cloud. Because the eBPF sensor operates below the application layer, Groundcover can auto-discover services and protocols across an entire cluster without manual configuration, and it natively supports OpenTelemetry for teams that already have existing instrumentation. On the feature side, Groundcover unifies logs, metrics, distributed traces, Kubernetes events, and infrastructure health into a single correlated view, with root-cause-analysis workflows designed to help engineers jump from an alert straight to the offending pod, container, or code path. The platform has also added AI observability capabilities aimed at teams running LLM-based applications and AI agents, letting them monitor prompts, model latency, token usage, and failures alongside traditional infrastructure and application telemetry. Security-relevant features include role-based access control (RBAC), single sign-on (SSO), and, on the higher tiers, isolated authentication and a fully self-hosted UI and data plane for organizations with strict data-residency or compliance requirements. Groundcover's pricing model is one of its most distinctive aspects. Rather than charging based on the volume of logs, metrics, or traces ingested, the dominant pricing model among observability vendors, Groundcover charges based on the monthly average number of Kubernetes nodes actively monitored by its eBPF sensor, regardless of node size or how much data that node generates. The Free plan monitors nodes with 12-hour data retention and community Slack support at no cost. The Pro plan is 30 dollars per host per month and adds all integrations and data sources, SSO, standard retention, and standard support. The Enterprise plan, at 35 dollars per host per month, adds RBAC, unlimited data retention, and premium support. The On-Premise plan, at 50 dollars per host per month, adds a fully self-hosted data plane, self-hosted UI, and isolated authentication. Because pricing is decoupled from data volume, customers can monitor environments such as development and staging clusters that they might otherwise leave dark under a traditional ingestion-priced observability bill. Groundcover's target audience is primarily platform engineering, DevOps, and SRE teams running production workloads on Kubernetes who want deep, correlated observability without the operational overhead of manually instrumenting every service or the unpredictable costs of ingestion-based billing. It competes most directly with Datadog, New Relic, Grafana Cloud, and other eBPF-native observability entrants. Its main differentiators are the combination of true zero-instrumentation data collection via eBPF, a BYOC architecture that keeps sensitive telemetry inside the customer's own cloud boundary, and node-based rather than ingestion-based pricing.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '66cb9934-6740-4aa9-bd5c-6b81c6f665af';

