-- ── Guru ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Guru is an AI-powered knowledge management platform that delivers verified, cited answers to employees inside Slack, browsers, and other everyday work tools.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (per seat, 10-seat minimum on paid plans)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$25/seat/month billed annually (30-day free trial, 10-seat minimum)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2013, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Philadelphia, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Guru Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Guru review covering its AI knowledge management platform, Slack integration, verified Knowledge Cards, pricing plans, key features, pros, cons, and alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Guru is a knowledge management and AI-powered internal search platform designed to give employees fast, trustworthy answers to work questions without having to dig through scattered wikis, shared drives, and chat history. Its core organizing unit is the Card, a short, verified piece of knowledge that subject-matter experts write and that other employees can trust because it carries an explicit verification status and expiration date, so outdated information gets flagged for review rather than silently going stale the way content in a traditional wiki often does. On top of that verified knowledge base, Guru layers AI-powered search and Knowledge Agents that can answer employee questions automatically inside the tools people already use, citing the underlying Cards so answers remain traceable back to a source rather than being an opaque AI-generated response. Guru was founded in 2013 by Rick Nucci and Mitchell Stewart and publicly launched in early 2014. The company is headquartered in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, and has been a prominent part of that city's tech startup scene. Guru raised a $25 million Series B round led by Thrive Capital in December 2018, and later raised a $30 million round led by Accel with participation from existing investors including Emergence Capital, FirstMark Capital, and Slack itself through the Slack Fund, along with Michael Dell's MSD Capital, bringing the company's total funding to roughly $68 to $71 million depending on the source. The involvement of Slack as an investor reflects how central Slack integration has been to Guru's product strategy from early on. Guru's Slack integration is one of its most developed distribution channels: once connected, Guru's Knowledge Agents can be attached to specific Slack channels and will automatically suggest verified answers to employee questions posted there, without requiring a slash command, while also letting teammates search and share Cards, capture new knowledge directly out of Slack conversations, and keep content verified, all without leaving Slack. Beyond Slack, Guru offers browser extensions and integrations with tools like Zendesk, Salesforce, and Jira, along with support for the Model Context Protocol so Guru's governed knowledge base can be surfaced inside other AI agents and assistants an organization uses. Enterprise-focused governance features include SOC 2 Type II, HIPAA, and GxP compliance certifications, single sign-on, SCIM provisioning, role-based access control, and data loss prevention and encryption controls, all aimed at organizations that need AI-generated answers to remain permission-aware and auditable rather than surfacing information a given employee shouldn't see. Guru's pricing is structured around three tiers: Starter, Builder, and an enterprise-oriented Expert tier, all sold per seat with a minimum purchase requirement. The Starter self-serve plan is priced at $25 per seat per month on annual billing, or $30 per seat per month if billed monthly, but requires a minimum of 10 seats, which puts the real floor at $250 per month annually or $300 per month on monthly billing. Guru does not publish list pricing for the Builder tier, which sits between Starter and Enterprise and adds AI Suggest, custom collections, advanced permissions, and integrations with tools like Salesforce, Zendesk, and Jira; pricing for Builder requires contacting Guru's sales team. The top Enterprise, or Expert, tier adds more advanced AI capabilities, premium analytics, dedicated support, and custom integrations, with pricing customized to deployment size and negotiated directly with sales. Guru does not offer a permanent free tier, but it does offer a 30-day free trial across its plans so teams can evaluate core features, integrations, and AI capabilities before committing, and it offers Guru for Good, a discounted pricing program for eligible 501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations. Guru's target audience spans customer-facing teams, including support, sales, and success, that need instant, accurate answers to close tickets and deals faster, as well as broader internal knowledge management for HR, IT, and operations teams at mid-market and enterprise companies. Its emphasis on verified, expiring, cited Cards makes it a particularly common fit for organizations in regulated or accuracy-sensitive industries where an AI assistant confidently answering a question with stale or unverified information carries real business risk. Competitively, Guru sits in the internal knowledge management and enterprise search category alongside tools like Confluence, Notion, Slab, Tettra, and newer AI-native workplace search tools like Glean. Its key differentiator versus a general-purpose wiki like Confluence or Notion is the built-in verification workflow, expiration dates, and permission-aware AI answers baked into the Card format itself, rather than knowledge freshness being left entirely to manual process discipline; and its differentiator versus broad enterprise search tools is a tighter focus on structured, curated Cards as the unit of trust, plus unusually deep, purpose-built Slack integration reflecting Slack's own early investment in the company.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '79fe800c-3b4a-461b-be9d-1206811b507d';

