-- ── Gusto ──────────────────────────────────────────────
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Gusto is a cloud-based payroll, benefits, and HR platform built for small and medium-sized businesses, handling payroll runs, tax filing, and employee benefits in one system.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$Subscription (base fee plus per-employee/per-month)$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE($q$$49/month base + $6/employee/month (Simple plan)$q$, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(2011, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$About 4,000 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$San Francisco, United States$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Gusto Review 2026: Features, Pricing and Alternatives$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Gusto review covering its payroll, benefits, and HR platform for small businesses, 2026 pricing plans, key features, pros, cons, and top alternatives.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Gusto is a cloud-based payroll, benefits, and human resources platform built for small and medium-sized businesses, designed to replace the patchwork of spreadsheets, outsourced payroll bureaus, and separate benefits brokers that many small companies rely on with a single, integrated system. It handles the core mechanics of running payroll, including automatic tax calculation, withholding, filing, and payment to federal, state, and local tax authorities, alongside direct deposit for employees and contractors, and layers on top of that HR functionality like employee onboarding, benefits administration, time tracking, and compliance support. The company was founded in 2011 by Joshua Reeves, Tomer London, and Edward Kim, and launched publicly on December 11, 2012 under the name ZenPayroll, before rebranding to Gusto in 2015 as the product expanded beyond payroll into a broader HR platform. Gusto is headquartered in San Francisco, California, and Joshua Reeves continues to serve as the company's CEO. Over its history, Gusto has raised a total of roughly $718 million in funding across nine rounds from 85 investors, reflecting substantial venture backing as it scaled from a payroll-only startup into a full HR platform. By early 2026, Gusto had surpassed $1 billion in annual revenue, putting it in the same revenue tier as HR and payroll competitors Deel and Rippling, while carrying a valuation of roughly $9.3 billion based on an employee tender offer that took place in June 2025. The company now serves more than 500,000 businesses nationwide and employs approximately 4,000 people as of 2026, up from roughly 3,100 in 2024. Gusto's core product is full-service payroll: the platform runs payroll on a flexible schedule, automatically calculates and withholds the correct federal, state, and local taxes for each employee or contractor, and files and remits those taxes on the employer's behalf, which removes one of the most error-prone and time-consuming tasks for a small business owner running payroll manually. Beyond payroll, Gusto offers benefits administration and brokerage services, letting small businesses offer health insurance, dental and vision coverage, 401(k) retirement plans, health savings accounts, and other employee perks and benefits, often at group rates that would be difficult for a very small employer to negotiate on its own. The platform also includes HR tools such as employee self-service portals, onboarding workflows, time tracking and PTO management, an employee directory, and compliance support around things like new-hire reporting and workers' compensation. Gusto supports both traditional W-2 employees and 1099 contractors, including contractor-only companies that don't need full payroll tax handling. Gusto's 2026 pricing follows a tiered, base-fee-plus-per-employee structure across three main plans. The Simple plan costs $49 per month as a base fee plus $6 per employee per month, and covers core full-service payroll, basic benefits administration, and employee self-service. The Plus plan costs $80 per month as a base fee plus $12 per employee per month, and adds more advanced HR tools such as time tracking, PTO management, and additional onboarding and compliance features on top of the payroll core. The Premium plan costs $180 per month as a base fee plus $22 per employee per month, and adds the most advanced HR functionality, including dedicated HR support and compliance resources aimed at larger or more complex small businesses. As a concrete example, a company with 10 employees would pay roughly $109 per month on the Simple plan, roughly $200 per month on Plus, and roughly $400 per month on Premium, before any additional add-ons like benefits brokerage fees. Gusto raised its Simple plan base price from $40 to $49 per month in March 2026. For businesses with no W-2 employees at all, Gusto also offers a dedicated Contractor Only plan priced at $35 per month plus $6 per month per contractor, which skips the payroll tax withholding and filing functionality that isn't needed for 1099-only relationships. Gusto's target audience is small and medium-sized businesses, typically ranging from solo founders with a handful of employees up through companies with a few hundred employees, who want an integrated payroll, benefits, and HR system rather than separate vendors for each function. Competitively, Gusto operates in the same broad payroll and HR software category as ADP, Paychex, QuickBooks Payroll, Rippling, and Deel. Its main differentiators relative to legacy payroll bureaus like ADP and Paychex are a modern, self-service software interface built specifically for small business owners rather than enterprise HR departments, transparent published pricing rather than opaque, negotiated enterprise contracts, and tightly integrated benefits brokerage and HR tools bundled directly into the payroll product rather than sold as bolt-on services. Relative to newer entrants like Rippling, which has pushed further into broader IT and device management alongside HR and payroll, Gusto has stayed more narrowly focused on payroll, benefits, and core HR for the small business segment specifically, which has helped it build a large, loyal base of more than 500,000 business customers even as it has grown into a company approaching and now exceeding $1 billion in annual revenue and a multi-billion-dollar valuation.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'fbffcaa4-b264-4a87-bd4b-d1c6cc1e9c14';

